    • Field Detail

      • ZERO

        public static final Num ZERO
        Constant ZERO.

        The design of ZERO is to simplify some operations. However, introducing this constant sometimes makes the situation more complicated. For example, ZERO has sign 0, forcing the originally boolean sign variable to be int. Besides, ZERO has base 0. This require of the asserion of this.base == other.base in the function must appear after isZero is verified.

      • SIGN_POSITIVE

        private static final int SIGN_POSITIVE
        Constant for positive sign. Sign of zero can be access as ZERO.sign.
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • SIGN_NEGATIVE

        private static final int SIGN_NEGATIVE

      • sign

        private final int sign
        The sign of the Num. -1 for negative, 0 for zero, 1 for positive number. Use int rather than boolean could eliminate duplicate representation of zero. Final keyword requires the sign be initialize in constructor.

      • numList

        private LinkedList<Long> numList
        The number is store in LinkedList with most significant digit at the end of the LinkedList, and the least significant digit at the beginning.

      • Num

        private Num​(LinkedList<Long> list,
            int sign,
            long base)
        Internal constructor used to create Num with same numList and specific sign, such as abs() or constant ZERO. Note that, the numList inside Num should be immutable in general. Operations on the numList inside Num often leads to new Num with newly allocated numList (for example add/subtract/product). Thus, copying the reference to the numList would be sufficient.
        Parameters:
        list - List allocated already.
        sign - New sign to the number.
        base - Radix of the number.
